==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mallows
<hw>Mal"lows</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
}</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>malwe</ets>, AS. <ets>mealwe</ets>,
fr. L. <ets>malva</ets>, akin to Gr. <grk>mala`chh</grk>; cf.
<grk>mala`ssein</grk> to soften, <grk>malako`s</grk> soft. Named either
from its softening or relaxing properties, or from its soft downy
leaves. Cf. <er>Mauve</er>, <er>Malachite</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>
<def>A genus of plants (<gen>Malva</gen>) having mucilaginous qualities.
See <er>Malvaceous</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The flowers of the common mallow (<spn>Malva
sylvestris</spn>) are used in medicine. The dwarf mallow (<spn>Malva
rotundifolia</spn>) is a common weed, and its flattened, dick-shaped
fruits are called <xex>cheeses</xex> by children. Tree mallow
(<spn>Malva Mauritiana</spn> and <spn>Lavatera arborea</spn>), musk
mallow (<spn>Malva moschata</spn>), rose mallow or hollyhock, and curled
mallow (<spn>Malva crispa</spn>), are less commonly seen.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Indian mallow</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Abutilon</er>.</cd>
-- <col><b>Jew's mallow</b></col>, <cd>a plant (<spn>Corchorus
olitorius</spn>) used as a pot herb by the Jews of Egypt and Syria.</cd>
-- <col><b>Marsh mallow</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Marsh</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mallow family</ent>⟦br⟧
